-- Hong Kong H-Shares Heading for Highest Since February
-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 2013-11-19T01:41:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-19/hong-kong-h-shares-heading-for-highest-since-february.html
Hong Kong   stocks  rose, with a gauge
of Chinese shares listed in the city headed for its highest
since February, as companies including insurers extended gains
from yesterday after China unveiled reform plans.  The  Hang Seng China Enterprises Index (HSCEI) , also known as the H-share index, added 1.7 percent to 11,499.72 as of 9:32 a.m. in
Hong Kong, headed for its highest close since Feb. 20. The  Hang
Seng Index (HSI)  added 0.5 percent to 23,780.86, with about twice as
many shares rising as falling. Data is expected to show a rise
in China foreign direct investment.  The  Hang Seng Index  advanced 19 percent from this year’s
low on June 24 through yesterday on signs  China’s economy  is
strengthening. The H-share index yesterday gained the most since
December 2011 as insurers to baby products soared after China
outlined a major policy shift. The Hang Seng Index  traded  at
11.3 times estimated earnings yesterday, compared with 16.2 for
the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index.  China may announce today foreign direct investment for
October increased 6.1 percent from a year earlier in October,
according to a median estimate of four economists surveyed by
Bloomberg. That compares with a 4.9 percent increase the
previous month.  Futures on the S&P 500 were little changed after the
underlying equity gauge dropped 0.4 percent yesterday from a
record. U.S. stocks have risen for the past six weeks, reaching
all-time highs after Fed nominee  Janet Yellen  signaled she will
continue stimulus to avoid recovery risks. The central bank
won’t taper its monthly asset purchases of $85 billion until
March, according economists surveyed by Bloomberg on Nov. 8.  To contact the reporter on this story:
